##################################################################
The shocking predatory strike of the electric eel - Catania 2014 (read on 29.04.25)

- E. electricus
- up to 600 V
- 3 ms after high V volley prey fish is paralyzed

mechanism of prey immobilisation:
- pithed fish, so only peripheral nerve and muscle reaction can be measured
- eel hunts worms
- pithed fish seperated from eel with agar plate (seperated mechanically but not electrically)
- 3-4 ms after first high V pulse fish contracted
- fish contraction is equally strong to maximum twitch that could be elicited on purpose
- electrically induced tetanus

muscle or nerve immobilisation:
- 2 fish next to each other behind agar barrier
- one fish treated with curare, other got saline
- fish w curare almost no muscle tension, other fish same amount as in prev experiments
- eels shock acts on nervous system of prey, specifically motor neurons
- high frequency and amplitude discharge very effective to immobilize

- fish in plastic bag and behind agar (isolated from eel in all senses but mechanically)
- if researcher makes fish twitch after doublet of eel; attack
- same response if fish twitched without probing doublet
- no attack if fish doesn't twitch after doublet


################ SUMMARY CATANIA PAPERS ################
- NEXT JOURNAL CLUB
usual hunting strategy of eel:
- probing environment with small V pulses
- then high V doublet, to force prey to twitch (mechanosensory detection)
- attack in direction of prey with high V volley
- prey immobilized after 3 ms
- if too big/tricky, eel concentrates electric field around it to put more force into paralyzing prey
- high V volley also used to very precisely sense prey location and confirm that is prey (electrosensory feedback necessary for feeding attempt)


