Biology of the electric eel, Electrophorus electricus, Linnaeus, 1766 (Gymnotiformes: Gymnotidae) on the floodplain of the Curiaú River, eastern Amazonia - Mendes-Junior 2015 (read on 2.2.26)

- lowkey boring basic info on how big they are as adults and when they sexually mature (app. 85 cm for females, males a bit bigger)
- use this info to argue for government rules to protect el. eels in nature (min size to be caught 85 cm, dont hunt in rainy season bc of mating and offspring)
- they took 1 eel per month over 2 (?) years from the wild and measured a bunch of physiological and anatomical stuff (gonad size, blood stuff, ...)

