MEMBRANE POTENTIALS IN THE ELECTROPLATES OF THE ELECTRIC EEL - KEYNES 1952 (read on 06.02.26)

- propose that mechanism behind high voltagte shocks are similar to impulse propagation in nerve and muscle
- EOD consists of multiple layers of electroplates
- electroplates consist of nervous and non--nervous face, nervous face points towards eels tail
- non nervous face has extremely low resistance (0.23 Ohmcm**2) - this is important so pulse can flow thourhg those cells without too much resistance
- electroplates are probably specialized muscle tissue
- potentials during pulse are additive across all electroplates
- used 2 microelectrodes and determined potential diff between them
- using direct coupled differential amplifier
- electrodes placed in small portion of electric tissue (~3 electroplates thick)
- E. electricus, 11 animals
- resting potential: -84 mV, same on both faces of electroplates (this verifies bernsteins hypothesis from 1912)
- shock: action potential of 150 mV on nervous face of each electroplate (potential reversal/overshoot)
- non-nervous face stays inactive
- 1.7 m/s propagation
- all or none response, i.e. spike only if enough potential there, otherwise no spike, threshhold potential at almost 12 mV
- spike shapes depend on temp, longer spikes on cooling
- avg. spike duration 2.4 ms at half peak amplitude
- peaks that are drawn in this paper have a small peak before the main peak
- small peak infront of big peak happens at the same time over the whole surface but the main pulse travels (fig. 15)
- at peak of spike the potential between the two faces of the electroplate switches due to the massive depolarization and all potentials are in series (and thus added up)
- head of eel becomes positive, tail negative, during discharge
- sachs and main organ are physiologically very different, suggesting that sachs has a specialized function other than increasing main organs output
- ALREADY showed that e. electricus can sense conductors in water & that search pulses originated from posterior end of el. organ (sachs organ?)

- Synchronität: whole surface of electroplate activated at virtually same time in a spike
- no meaningful propagation of the spike, therefore conceptually more similar to squid axon in voltage/space clamp than normal axon
- eel electroplate reflects membrane dynamics, not cable propagation
- upstream control of synchronization: Spinal electromotor neurons with very large, fast, myelinated axons, firing in highly synchronized bursts
- electroplates activated by this synced firing
- High density of voltage-gated Na⁺ channels on the innervated face, low excitability on the opposite face, prevents circular or traveling excitation
- single, uniform dipole per plate, no internal waves running around the membrane

##################################################################
Ontogeny of the Electric Organs in the Electric Eel, Electrophorus electricus : Physiological, Histological, and Fine Structural Investigations - Horst O. Schwassmann 2014 (read on 10.02.26)

- talk about how electric organs develop from embrionic to juveline states
- e. electricus
- main finding: electrocytes are not modified muscle cells but originate directly from electromatrix i.e. germinative region
- first main organ develops, then sachs organ (at 12 cm length)
- EOD onset at 7 days old larvae
- adult EOD pattern at 45 mm length
- electroplates are sperated by electrosepta (bindegewebe)
- longitudinal electrosepta seperate columns of electrocytes
- median septum seperates both halves of later main organ
- electrosepta are necessary for correct innervation and electric activity
- structural analysis also verifies that electrocytes are distinct from and dont originiate from muscle cells
- actin like filaments in electrocytes (propably important to make them flat)
- behavior changes drastically relating to ontogenesis of electric organs
- swimming: oriented swwimming in larvae from 6-10 days, before that larvae sinnk to ground if they fall out of nest
- first swimming like snake, from length 30-40mm on, they use anal fin and sideways movement of tail for swimming
- high V burtsts from length of 35 mm
- reaction to mechanical or electrical stimuli from 22-30 mm
- high volume hum in nests (eachb larvae pulses normal but loud bc of group)
- clear differentiation into low and high V pulses from 45 mm length (important point in development)

##################################################################
Unexpected species diversity in electric eels with a description of the strongest living bioelectricity generator - David de Santana (read on 11.02.26)

- first paper that shows that there are 3 instead of 1 electrophorus species
- based on genetic, morphological and ecological distribution
- morphological: skull shape and depth, pectoral fin rays, cleithrum position
- ecological: conductivity, oxygen level, rapids vs floodplains
- e. voltai and varii described as new species in this paper
- electricus:
    - guiana shield
    - u shaped head
    - 88-101 lateral line pores
    - 480 V discharge
    - 2,03 bis 2,19 ms sachs organ waveform
- varii:
    - lowland flood plains , intercratonic basin
    - low cond. blackwaters and high cond whitewaters, normoxic streams and hypoxic floodplains, slow flowing, no rocky substrate
    - 572 V discharge
    - 124-186 lateral line pores
    - deepened skull
    -  1,24 bis 1,78 ms sachs organ waveform
    - breeds in dry period so offspring is independent in wet season
- voltai:
    - brazilian shield
    - normal oxygen level, low conductivity, rocky ground/rapids/waterfalls
    - egg shaped head
    - 860 V discharge (strongest recorded)
    - 1,72 ms sachs organ waveform (assumed)
- voltai and varii cooccur in some streams in guiana shield
- voltai and varii may have diverged due to adjustment to these different habitats (reflected by head morphology, different for difference in water speed)
- there are differences in waveform but they dont correlate with phylogeny
- langth of sachs organ pulse is different for each species, esp. for voltai and varii
- reason for different length of EOD in varii and voltai might be their sympatric occurance (reproductive character displacement)

