Nesting and Paternal Care in the Weakly Electric Fish Gymnotus (Gymnotiformes: Gymnotidae) with Descriptions of Larval and Adult Electric Organ Discharges of Two Species - Crampton & Hopkins (read on 11.02.26)

- looked at gymnotus carapo (trinidad) and mamiraua (amazon whitewater floodplains)
- males guard eggs and juveniles strongly
- females absent from nests
- estimated that offspring disperse on their on after 8-12 weeks
- carapo has mouthbrooding
- strong differences between juvenile and adult EODs
- larval: monophasic, low power, low freq
- adult: multiphasic waveform, higher peak power freq, higher freq at night than at day
- airbreathing due to living in hypoxic waters
- how much can I compare this to el. eel ???

##################################################################
HISTÓRIA NATURAL DE PORAQUÊS (ELECTROPHORUS SPP.) - DOUGLAS AVIZ BASTOS (read on 13.02.26)

- first two chapters are in portuguese so I didnt get much of that
- tracked several E. varii for 2 years in Ducke with PIT tags so they know where which animal was at all times
- but interesting info like: species that are strongly intermittent electric fish
- number and location of adult and juvenile eels in ducke
- timeline for courtship, breeding behavior, reproductive period in different areas!! figure 2.7
- up to 180 days of parental care!
- high investment in each offsprings survival (eqilibrium strategist)
- iteropar i.e. can have multiple offsprings in 1 lifecycle
- E. varii reproduction cycle starts in dry season (very unsusual for amazonian fish) (june - august in manaus, sept-nov in marajo)
- offspring is independent in wet season (more food in wet season for young eels)
- when wet season starts young eels are 15 cm (after app. 4 months)
- brooding places only accessible when water level is low enough
- brooding places are in higher up smaller streams (headwaters) or at the edge of lakes
- eels travel to brooding places in groups (reproductive migration)
- same brooding places are being revisited by eels each year (its not known if these are the exact same eels right? maybe competition for best brooding places?)
- males build bubble nests, these keep the eggs above the water surface but still moist
- female feeds larvae with unfertilized eggs (trophische oozyten) twice during first days/weeks
- eggs hatch at day 5
- male guards nest
- other species seem to reproduce during wet season and have less parental care time
- e. varii wurde als sehr standorttreu beobachtet
- somewhat linear growth of juvenile eels (fig 2.2)
- detailed description of entwicklung from egg over larvae to juvenile eels
- umweltparameter zu nestern der Zitteraale

